{Lesson four. Encirclement.   A long siege of the opponent is best known from
middle games with a closed centre. The opponent is slowly crushed through the
flanks. Encirclement also occurs in the endgame. An interesting case is the
decisive game in Sevilla 1987. Kasparov trails by 11-12 and has to win the
adjourned game in order to keep the title.} 42. Kg2 {White is able to attack
with queen and bishop on the left flank. The h- and g-pawns can advance at the
other side.} 42... g6 $5 {Karpov enlarges his fortress, because he fears an
attack on the kingside. If a pawn is admitted to h5, an advance to g5 can
start.} 43. Qa5 Qg7 44. Qc5 Qf7 45. h4 h5 $6 ({Kasparov prefers} 45... Kg7 {
White will play} 46. g4 {and 47.g5. This allows an exchange on g5. Thereafter
a pawn advances to e5 and White will win anyway.}) 46. Qc6 Qe7 47. Bd3 Qf7 48.
Qd6 Kg7 49. e4 $1 Kg8 50. Bc4 Kg7 51. Qe5+ Kg8 {Black has to remain passive.} (
51... Qf6 52. Qc7+ Qf7 53. Qxf7+ Kxf7 54. e5 Nd7 55. f4 $18 {The bishop is
aimed at g6 and white's king marches to the queenside. The weaknesses e6 and
g6 are fatal for Black.}) 52. Qd6 Kg7 53. Bb5 Kg8 54. Bc6 Qa7 55. Qb4 $1 Qc7
56. Qb7 Qd8 ({Even} 56... Qxb7 57. Bxb7 e5 {does not save the game.}) 57. e5 $1
{The encirclement has been completed. Black misses a pawn on f7 dearly. White
conquers square f7 and thus penetrate the fortress.} 57... Qa5 (57... Qd3 58.
Be8 Qf5 59. Qf3 $1 {(Kasparov).}) 58. Be8 Qc5 59. Qf7+ Kh8 60. Ba4 Qd5+ 61. Kh2
Qc5 62. Bb3 Qc8 63. Bd1 Qc5 64. Kg2 {Black can only move his queen in the
final position. Karpov resigned and Kasparov kept the world title.} ({
Kasparov analyses} 64. Kg2 Qb4 65. Bf3 Qc5 66. Be4 Qb4 67. f3 $1 (67. Bxg6 $4
Nxg6 68. Qxg6 Qb7+ 69. Kh2 Qg2+ $1 70. Kxg2) 67... Qd2+ 68. Kh3 Qb4 (68... Qh6
69. f4 Qg7 70. Qxg7+ Kxg7 71. Bc6 $18) 69. Bxg6 Nxg6 70. Qxg6 Qxh4+ 71. Kg2 $1
$18) 1-0

