{Lesson five. Blockade in general.   The aim of prophylaxis is to take away
possibilities from the opponent. Blockade, the simplest prophylaxis, will be
treated. If a piece is placed before a pawn, three advantages exist: the pawn
cannot advance, the pawn gives some protection to the blockader and the
blockader restricts the hostile mobility (Nimzowitsch). The example shows the
advantages of blockade in an elementary way.} 58. Rf1 $1 {Black has a backward
f-pawn. White has to take advantage immediately. Otherwise Black will
eliminate his only weakness.} 58... Kb8 $6 {The king will attack the a-pawn.} (
{More problems sets} 58... Kd6 59. Rf6+ Ke7 60. g5 hxg5 61. hxg5 Rc7 (61... Rd6
62. Rxd6 Kxd6 63. Ke4 {and White wins the pawn ending (Gligoric)}) 62. Kc3 Rc8
63. Kb4 Rh8 $1 (63... Ra8 {The attack on the queenside is stopped.} 64. d5 $1
cxd5 65. cxd5 Rd8 66. Kc5 $18) 64. a6 $1 bxa6 65. Rxc6 Rh5 66. Rxa6 Rxg5 67.
Ra7+ {White has an advantage in time. Probably, this will suffice for the win.}
) 59. Rf6 {The advantages of a blockade can be noticed: the f-pawn cannot be
moved, the blockader cannot be attacked and the blocader pressures on the
sixth rank.} 59... Ka7 60. h5 Ka6 61. g5 $1 {White has a nice decision.} 61...
hxg5 62. h6 Kxa5 63. h7 Rd8 64. Rxf7 b5 65. cxb5 Kxb5 (65... cxb5 {
creates a second passed pawn for White.}) 66. Rb7+ $1 {White gains a tempo.}
66... Ka6 67. Rg7 Rh8 68. Ke4 Kb5 69. Kf3 Kc4 70. Rd7 Kd3 71. Kg4 Rxh7 72. Rxh7
Kxd4 73. Rd7+ (73. Rd7+ {Again White wins a move.} 73... Kc4 74. Rc7 Kd5 75.
Kf3 $18) 1-0

