{Lesson eleven. Strong and weak squares.  A square in or close to the own
position is strong if it can be controlled and possibly occupied (a definition
after Euwe and Reti). It is irrelevant if the square is occupied or empty. If
a square is controlled by a pawn, the opponent cannot control it (Euwe in
Tijdschrift 1929). Therefore we consider the pawn structure as essential when
we search for strong squares.  At the start of the next endgame, the squares
b3, b2, d3 and f4 are strong for Black. The square d5 is strong for White. The
squares b5, e5 and g6 are not strong for White, because it is hardly possible
to control them. So White has four strong square and White one.} 45... Nd3 $6 (
45... Nb3 $1 46. Ke2 Bf4 47. Na6 Bg3 {utilises the weak squares.}) 46. Nd1 Bc1
47. Ke2 $1 {Keres has set a wonderful trap.} 47... Nc5 (47... Nxb2 $2 48. Nxb2
Bxb2 49. Kd2 Bxa3 50. Kc2 Bxb4 51. cxb4 {
Black has won two pawns, but White has an impregnable fortress.}) 48. Kf3 g5
49. hxg5 Bxg5 50. Na2 Ke6 51. Nf2 Kf6 52. Nd1 Nd3 53. g3 Kg6 54. Kg2 Bd2 55.
Kf3 Kg5 56. Ke2 Be1 57. Kf3 Bd2 58. Ke2 Be1 59. Kf3 Kf6 60. Kg2 ({
Elegancy shows} 60. Nb4 Nxb4 61. cxb4 Bd2 $1 62. Ke2 Bc1 $1 63. Nc3 Bxb2 64.
Nxb5 Kg5 {(Barcza).}) 60... Kg6 $6 (60... Nc5 $1 61. Kf3 Ne6 62. g4 h4 $19) 61.
Kf3 Kg5 62. Kg2 h4 63. gxh4+ Kf4 $6 ({Black makes progress in} 63... Bxh4 64.
Kf3 Ne1+ 65. Ke3 Kg4) 64. h5 Kxe4 65. h6 Nf4+ 66. Kf1 Bh4 67. Nb4 Bf6 68. Ke1
Kf3 69. h7 Bg7 {Strong squares for Black are b3, b2, d3, h8 and h7. Strong for
White are b5 and g8. Black's great positional can be expressed in numbers this
way.} 70. Nc2 $2 (70. Nc6 $1 Nd3+ 71. Kd2 {The e-pawn will be stopped. It is
dangerous to conquer the h-pawn, because the active knight on c6 will attack
the weakness b5.}) 70... Nd5 $1 71. Kd2 Nf6 72. Ne1+ Ke4 73. Nf2+ Kf5 74. Ng2
Nxh7 {Black has won a pawn and finishes the game quietly.} 75. Ne3+ Ke6 76. Ne4
Bh6 77. Ke2 Bxe3 $1 78. Kxe3 Nf6 79. Ng5+ Kd5 80. Kf3 Nh5 81. Ne4 Nf4 82. Nf6+
Kc6 83. Ke4 Nd3 84. Ng4 Kd6 85. Nh6 Nxb2 $1 86. Nf7+ Kc5 87. Nxe5 Nd1 88. Nd7+
Kd6 89. Kd4 Nxc3 {The players produced a great positional game despite the
inaccuracies.  Counting strong and weak squares is a useful technique. If
strong squares are found near the own position, this gives information about
the restriction of the opponent. Appropriate consolidation leads to strong
squares in the own territory. Strong and weak pawns are found in the process.
This approach gives a useful source of information to human and computer.} 0-1

