{Lesson twenty. Zugzwang. The aim of a positional manoeuvre is to lose time in
order to strengthen the own position or to weaken the opponent. This time such
a manoeuvre leads to zugzwang. The tormented chess player would like to skip a
move but that violates the rules. The next fragment stems from a chess
tournament among nine world champions of correspondence chess.  } 31. h4 $1 {
Umansky can win the exchange but he betters his position firstly.} 31... Rc8
32. h5 $1 c4 $1 33. Kg2 a5 34. a4 $1 {
Black has to weaken his position due to mutual zugzwang.} ({Premature is} 34.
e7 $2 Kf7 35. e8=Q+ Rxe8 36. Nxe8+ Kxe8 37. Kf2 {due to} 37... Ng4+ $1) 34...
g4 $5 {He takes square g4 from his knight.} ({The complex variation} 34... Ra8
$5 35. Nd7 $1 Nxd7 36. Rf7+ Kg8 37. Rxd7 Rc8 38. Kf3 $1 c3 39. Ke3 c2 40. Kd2
c6 $1 41. Kxc2 cxd5+ 42. Kd3 Kf8 43. Kd4 Rc4+ 44. Kxd5 Rxa4 45. Rf7+ Ke8 46.
Kxd6 Ra3 47. g4 Rd3+ 48. Ke5 Re3+ 49. Kf6 Rf3+ 50. Kg7 {
leads to a White win (after Umansky).}) 35. e7 $1 Kf7 36. e8=Q+ Rxe8 37. Nxe8+
Kxe8 38. Kf2 Ke7 39. Ke3 c6 40. Ke4 Nf3 ({Or} 40... c5 41. Kf5 $1 Nd3 42. Kg6
c3 43. Kxh6 {and the h-pawn decides the game (Umansky).}) 41. Rc1 c5 42. Kf5
Ne5 43. Rc2 $1 Kf7 44. Rb2 Nd3 45. Rb7+ Kf8 46. Kf6 $1 Ke8 47. Ke6 Kf8 48. Rf7+
Kg8 49. Rf1 {The win caused a sensation. Umansky became the champion of
champions by an impressive score of 7/8. Palciauskas, Timmerman and Baumbach
shared rthe second place.} (49. Rf1 c3 50. Kxd6 $1 c2 51. Kc7 c1=Q 52. Rxc1
Nxc1 53. d6 {and the d-pawn rules.}) 1-0

