{Lesson twenty-one. Positional sacrifice: win. Material is sacrificed in order
to strengthen the own position or weaken the opponent. This sacrifice rarely
occurs in practice. A bishop is given in order to achieve the win in this
example. White controls the d-file and exerts pressure of the f-file.  } 27.
Rh3 $1 Ne7 28. Rf3 Rhf8 29. Rd6 $1 a5 30. g5 $1 {
The attack on the kingside begins.} 30... hxg5 ({The immediate} 30... Nf5 $6 {
allows the positional sacrifice} 31. gxh6 gxh6 32. Rxf5 $1 exf5 33. Rxh6 $1 Rh8
34. Rf6 {(Kramnik).}) 31. Bxg5 Nf5 $1 {The knight has to control h6. Pawn f7
needs indirect protection. Black has lost the struggle for the d-file, because
the knight cannot go to d5 and square d8 cannot be occupied by a rook.} 32. Rd1
a4 33. b4 {Black has to look for counter-play, if he wants to survive.} 33...
Kc8 $2 {Black becomes completely passive.} ({The counterattack} 33... Rh8 $1
34. Rfd3 Raf8 $1 {develops the rooks and attacks a pawn.} 35. Rd7+ Kb8 $1 {
White has not a decisive attack (Lukacs).}) 34. Rfd3 Ra7 35. Rd8+ Rxd8 36.
Rxd8+ Kb7 37. Kc3 Ka6 38. Kd3 $1 Rc7 39. Ke4 Kb7 40. Rd1 Kc8 41. Rd8+ Kb7 42.
Kf4 $1 Rc8 43. Rd7+ Rc7 44. Rd3 Kc8 ({Black repeats the moves because} 44...
Rc8 {fails due to} 45. Bd8) 45. Rd8+ Kb7 {An unexpected decision occurs.} 46.
Bf6 $3 {White brings a magnificent positional sacrifice. He threatens with the
continuation 47.Bxg7.} 46... g6 (46... gxf6 47. exf6 Rc8 48. Rxc8 Kxc8 49. Kg5
$1 Kd7 50. h6 Nxh6 51. Kxh6 e5 52. Kh7 $1 {
and White wins the tempo play (Kramnik):} 52... e4 53. Kg7 Ke6 54. a3) 47. hxg6
fxg6 48. Kg5 {Kramnik plays a perfect combination of combinatory struggle and
subtle prophylaxis.} 1-0

